# Java Programming Fundamentals - Session Plan

## Session Overview
Duration: 2 hours
Target Audience: Complete beginners to programming
Prerequisites: Computer with internet access

## 1. Introduction (15 minutes)

### What is Java?
- A versatile, object-oriented programming language
- "Write once, run anywhere" capability
- Used in Android development, web applications, enterprise software

### Why Learn Java?
- Large community and extensive resources
- Strong job market demand
- Excellent foundation for learning other programming languages

## 2. Environment Setup (20 minutes)

### Required Software
1. Java Development Kit (JDK)
   - Download from Oracle website
   - Verify installation: `java -version`

2. IDE Installation
   - IntelliJ IDEA Community Edition (recommended)
   - Alternative: Eclipse

### First Program
```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

## 3. Basic Syntax and Structure (30 minutes)

### Data Types
```java
// Primitive Types
int age = 25;
double salary = 50000.50;
boolean isStudent = true;
char grade = 'A';

// Reference Types
String name = "John Doe";
```

### Variables and Operators
```java
// Variable declaration and initialization
int x = 10;
int y = 5;

// Arithmetic operators
int sum = x + y;
int difference = x - y;
int product = x * y;
int quotient = x / y;

// Comparison operators
boolean isGreater = x > y;
boolean isEqual = x == y;
```

### Control Flow
```java
// If-else statement
int score = 85;
if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.out.println("Grade: B");
} else {
    System.out.println("Grade: C");
}

// For loop
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Count: " + i);
}

// While loop
int count = 0;
while (count < 3) {
    System.out.println("Loop iteration: " + count);
    count++;
}
```

## 4. Hands-On Exercise (25 minutes)

### Temperature Converter Program
Task: Create a program that converts temperatures between Celsius and Fahrenheit.

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class TemperatureConverter {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.println("Temperature Converter");
        System.out.println("1. Celsius to Fahrenheit");
        System.out.println("2. Fahrenheit to Celsius");
        System.out.print("Enter your choice (1 or 2): ");

        int choice = scanner.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter temperature: ");
        double temp = scanner.nextDouble();

        if (choice == 1) {
            double fahrenheit = (temp * 9/5) + 32;
            System.out.printf("%.1f°C = %.1f°F%n", temp, fahrenheit);
        } else if (choice == 2) {
            double celsius = (temp - 32) * 5/9;
            System.out.printf("%.1f°F = %.1f°C%n", temp, celsius);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid choice!");
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

## 5. Object-Oriented Programming Concepts (25 minutes)

### Classes and Objects
```java
// Class definition
public class Student {
    // Fields (attributes)
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // Constructor
    public Student(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // Methods
    public void introduce() {
        System.out.println("Hi, I'm " + name + " and I'm " + age + " years old.");
    }
}

// Creating and using objects
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student student1 = new Student("Alice", 20);
        student1.introduce();
    }
}
```

### Inheritance Example
```java
// Parent class
public class Animal {
    protected String name;

    public Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Some sound");
    }
}

// Child class
public class Dog extends Animal {
    public Dog(String name) {
        super(name);
    }

    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }
}
```

## 6. Wrap-up and Resources (15 minutes)

### Key Takeaways
- Java basics: variables, data types, control flow
- Object-oriented programming fundamentals
- Practical coding experience

### Additional Resources
1. Oracle Java Documentation
2. Java Tutorial for Beginners (w3schools)
3. Practice platforms:
   - CodeGym
   - HackerRank
   - CodingBat

### Homework Assignment
Extend the Temperature Converter program to:
- Handle invalid inputs
- Add more temperature scales (Kelvin)
- Implement a loop to convert multiple temperatures

## Next Steps
- Practice writing simple programs
- Study Java collections framework
- Learn about exception handling
- Explore file I/O operations

</Antartifact>

